{"award_age":64.0,"bio_image":null,"category":"Peace","country":"France","date_of_birth":"1843-05-21T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1918-02-08T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":[],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Louis_Renault_(jurist)","mini_bio":"<p><b>Louis Renault<\/b> (May 21, 1843 \u2013 February 8, 1918) was a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/France\" title=\"France\">French<\/a> jurist and educator, the cowinner in 1907 (with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ernesto_Teodoro_Moneta\" title=\"Ernesto Teodoro Moneta\">Ernesto Teodoro Moneta<\/a>) of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_for_Peace\" title=\"Nobel Prize for Peace\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Nobel Prize for Peace<\/a>.<\/p><p>Renault was born at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Autun\" title=\"Autun\">Autun<\/a>. From 1868 to 1873 Renault was professor of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Roman_law#Roman_law_today\" title=\"Roman law\">Roman<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Commercial_law\" title=\"Commercial law\">commercial law<\/a> at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Dijon\" title=\"University of Dijon\" class=\"mw-redirect\">University of Dijon<\/a>. From 1873 until his death he was professor in the faculty of law at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Paris\" title=\"University of Paris\">University of Paris<\/a>, where in 1881 he became professor of international law. In 1890 he was appointed <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Jurisconsult\" title=\"Jurisconsult\" class=\"mw-redirect\">jurisconsult<\/a> of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, a post created for him in which he scrutinized French foreign policy in the light of international law. He served at numerous conferences in this capacity, notably at the two <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hague_Conventions_(1899_and_1907)\" title=\"Hague Conventions (1899 and 1907)\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Hague Conventions (1899 and 1907)<\/a> and the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/London_Naval_Conference\" title=\"London Naval Conference\">London Naval Conference<\/a> of 1908-09.<\/p><p>Renault was prominent as an arbitrator, his more famous cases including the Japanese House Tax case of 1905, the Casa Blanca Case of 1909, the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Vinayak_Damodar_Savarkar#Savarkar_case_before_the_Permanent_Court_of_Arbitration\" title=\"Vinayak Damodar Savarkar\">Sarvarkar Case<\/a> of 1911, the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Carthage\" title=\"Carthage\">Carthage<\/a> case of 1913, and the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Manouba\" title=\"Manouba\">Manouba<\/a> case of 1913. Among his writings are articles and monographs on the specialized topics of international law. Together with his friend and colleague C. Lyon-Caen, he produced several works on commercial law, including a compendium in two volumes, a treatise in eight volumes, and a manual that ran to many editions.<\/p><p>In 1879 Renault published his Introduction to the Study of International Law and in 1917 First Violations of International Law by Germany, concerning the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Western_Front_(World_War_I)#1914.E2.80.94German_invasion_of_France_and_Belgium\" title=\"Western Front (World War I)\">invasion of Belgium<\/a> and of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Luxembourg\" title=\"Luxembourg\">Luxembourg<\/a> in breach of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Germany\" title=\"Germany\">Germany<\/a>'s treaty obligations.<\/p><p><br><\/p><p><br><\/p>","name":"Louis Renault","place_of_birth":null,"place_of_death":null,"text":"Louis Renault , Peace, 1907","year":1907.0}